#  Contributing Guide

Thank you for your interest in contributing to the Solana KYC Compliance SDK! This document provides guidelines and instructions for contributors.

## Code of Conduct

Please read and follow our [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md).

## Getting Started

### 1. Fork the Repository
```bash
# Fork on GitHub, then clone your fork
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/solana-kyc-compliance-sdk.git
cd solana-kyc-compliance-sdk
```

2. Set Up Development Environment

```bash
# Install dependencies
npm install

# Build the project
npm run build:sdk
npm run build:program

# Run tests
npm test
```

3. Create a Branch

```bash
git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
# or
git checkout -b fix/issue-description
```

Development Workflow

1. Rust Program Development

```bash
# Build and test Rust program
cd programs/kyc-compliance
cargo build
cargo test

# Build for Solana
cargo build-bpf

# Format code
cargo fmt
```

2. TypeScript SDK Development

```bash
# Build SDK
npm run build:sdk

# Run TypeScript compiler in watch mode
npx tsc --watch

# Run tests
npm test
npm run test:sdk
```

3. Running Examples

```bash
# Test your changes with examples
npm run example:register
npm run example:token
npm run example:transfer
npm run example:admin
```

Contribution Areas

High Priority

1. Security fixes - Critical security vulnerabilities
2. Bug fixes - Functionality that doesn't work as documented
3. Performance improvements - Significant performance enhancements
4. Documentation - Improved docs, examples, guides

Medium Priority

1. New features - Well-designed new functionality
2. Test coverage - Additional tests and edge cases
3. Code quality - Refactoring and improvements
4. Developer experience - Better DX, error messages, etc.

Low Priority

1. Cosmetic changes - Code formatting, naming, etc.
2. Minor enhancements - Small improvements
3. Experimental features - Proof-of-concept features

Pull Request Process

1. Before Submitting

路 Run npm test and ensure all tests pass
路 Run cargo test for Rust changes
路 Update documentation if needed
路 Add tests for new functionality
路 Ensure code follows style guidelines

2. PR Description Template

```markdown
## Description
Brief description of the changes

## Type of Change
- [ ] Bug fix
- [ ] New feature
- [ ] Breaking change
- [ ] Documentation update
- [ ] Other (please describe)

## Testing
- [ ] Added/updated tests
- [ ] All tests pass
- [ ] Manual testing performed

## Checklist
- [ ] Code follows style guidelines
- [ ] Comments added where needed
- [ ] Documentation updated
- [ ] No new warnings

## Related Issues
Fixes # (issue number)
```

3. Code Review Process

4. Automated Checks - CI runs tests and linting
5. Maintainer Review - At least one maintainer reviews
6. Address Feedback - Make requested changes
7. Merge Approval - Maintainer approves and merges

Code Style Guidelines

Rust Code

```rust
// Use Rust 2021 edition features
// Follow clippy recommendations
// Use meaningful variable names
// Add doc comments for public items

/// Register a new investor
/// 
/// # Arguments
/// * `investor_data` - Investor information
/// 
/// # Returns
/// Transaction signature
pub async fn register_investor(
    investor_data: InvestorData
) -> Result<String, ComplianceError> {
    // Implementation
}
```

TypeScript Code

```typescript
// Use TypeScript strict mode
// Follow ESLint rules
// Use interfaces over types when possible
// Add JSDoc comments for public methods

/**
 * Get wallet compliance status
 * @param wallet - Wallet public key
 * @returns Wallet status and compliance data
 */
async getStatus(wallet: PublicKey): Promise<WalletStatus> {
  // Implementation
}
```

Documentation

路 Use Markdown for documentation
路 Include code examples
路 Update README.md if API changes
路 Add JSDoc for all public methods

Testing Guidelines

Unit Tests

```typescript
// tests/unit/client.test.ts
describe('ComplianceClient', () => {
  it('should register investor', async () => {
    // Test implementation
  });
});
```

Integration Tests

```typescript
// tests/integration/registration.test.ts
describe('Registration Integration', () => {
  before(async () => {
    // Setup test environment
  });
  
  it('should register and verify on-chain', async () => {
    // Test with actual blockchain
  });
});
```

Test Coverage

路 Aim for 80%+ test coverage
路 Test edge cases and error conditions
路 Mock external dependencies
路 Test both success and failure paths

Security Considerations

Critical Areas

1. Admin functions - Multi-sig, authorization
2. PDA generation - Correct seeds and bumps
3. Input validation - Validate all inputs
4. Error handling - Don't expose sensitive info

Security Checklist

路 No hardcoded private keys
路 Input validation on all endpoints
路 Proper error messages (no info leakage)
路 Rate limiting where appropriate
路 Audit trail for admin actions

Release Process

Versioning

We follow Semantic Versioning:

路 MAJOR - Breaking changes
路 MINOR - New features (backwards compatible)
路 PATCH - Bug fixes

Release Steps

1. Prepare Release Branch
   ```bash
   git checkout -b release/v1.2.0
   ```
2. Update Version
   ```bash
   # Update package.json
   npm version 1.2.0
   
   # Update Cargo.toml
   cargo set-version 1.2.0
   ```
3. Update Changelog
   ```bash
   # Add to CHANGELOG.md
   # Include all changes since last release
   ```
4. Create Pull Request
   ```bash
   git push origin release/v1.2.0
   # Create PR for review
   ```
5. Merge and Tag
   ```bash
   git tag v1.2.0
   git push --tags
   ```
6. Publish to NPM
   ```bash
   npm publish
   ```

Community

Communication Channels

路 GitHub Issues - Bug reports and feature requests
路 GitHub Discussions - Questions and discussions
路 Discord - Real-time chat and support

Recognition

Contributors will be:

路 Listed in CONTRIBUTORS.md
路 Acknowledged in release notes
路 Given credit for their work

Getting Help

Common Issues

1. Build failures - Check Node.js and Rust versions
2. Test failures - Ensure local validator is running
3. Deployment issues - Check Solana CLI configuration

Asking Questions

When asking for help, include:

1. What you're trying to do
2. What you've tried
3. Error messages
4. Environment details

License

By contributing, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the project's MIT License.

---

Thank you for contributing to making on-chain compliance better for everyone! 
EOF